<br>
It was a balmy 10 below zero out on the tundra and the bears must have been hibernating, because not a hair or hide could be found. After given up the search me and my grandfather, Cheii, decided to camp and make our way back in the morning. We flipped a gold to see who would be on first watch and of course I won the early bird special. I have to get a better look at that coin next time. So, fast asleep I went listening to my Cheii chant softly in the background...<br>
<br>
In a haze I was abruptly awoken. &quot;Get that lazy carcus ya call Baeron up! Tis ye watch.&quot; I began to protest but alas he had a heavy boot and my ribs were still tender from the first blow. Up and about, I began relighting the fire. <br>
&quot;Did ya see anything Cheii?&quot; I said. To my surprise the ol' cus was fast asleep. I sat back on a nearby rock and gazed up to the moon of Luclin. T'was then that I knew I'd been had. The moon had yet to fully rise. That be a full two candle marks extra the ol' man had given me. I began to chuckle at the benefits of an Elder and someday reapin' my reward from my grandson. As I sat I gazed out beyond the firelight and watched my imagination carry me away. Could that be a three eyed sapsucker, or the dreaded Vox and his minions surrounding my camp. Maybe haps be a pack of wolves lying in wait fer me to nap. Nay I will not fall asleep. Up I rose and wandered just outside campfire light and chose a high rock to make my perch. Nothing about, guess this hunt was fer not. I was startled when my Cheii walked up behind me and lightly cupped me on the shoulder. <br>
&quot;Be not startled. Just I,&quot; said my Cheii. &quot;Tonight the sky is just right. Mayhaps we will see the whipering winds.&quot;<br>
&quot;Dah winds?&quot; I said.<br>
&quot;Aye, sit and be still. Maybe I'll tell ya.&quot;<br>
So there we sat upon a high rock. T'was almost another candle mark before he gathered his thoughts. I think he may have gone back to sleep, but I said not.<br>
&quot;The whispering winds...&quot; he started. &quot;If I tell ya yous gotta take the next weeks last watch. Promise or nah story.&quot;<br>
&quot;Agreed,&quot; I said reluctantly. A barter to his dying day he'll be.<br>
<br>
When ya lose a comrade in arms or a loved one they may have the chance to become part of the whispering winds. The wind is made up of those closest to us all and it is they that watch over us. But like any thing they too have rules to how it could be done. In the early morning before the sun rises fully and the night sets there is a time of false dawn. This be the time when morning dew gathers and all the animals either go to sleep or get up. Tis also the quietest time here on the tundra. This be there time. As the dawn approaches and night fades away it is they who whisper to ya in he morn. Get up they say. Awake to a new dawn. Walk in harmony and beauty accept my gift of life. If yas a lazy cuss then they will take away there gifts. This is out of harmony and be very bad. So ya have to be up by dawn to greet ya elders. <br>
<br>
&quot;As I do you now...&quot; he said with sadness in his voice. <br>
The dawn has approached and with it his time had gone. <br>
&quot;What?!&quot; I said startled yet again.<br>
&quot;Aye, be my time. Look over yander.&quot; And over at camp I looked to see my Cheii gathered in his blankets asleep still. <br>
&quot;But ya asleep dar? Ya be fine just get back in ya body ya ol' coot!&quot; angered that this mayhap be the last time we argue.<br>
&quot;Nah! I's done here ya know enough to survive and my jobs done,&quot; he said in a calm voice. Away he walk off the rock. <br>
&quot;Wait,&quot; I said. Urgently now I climbed down. &quot;wait don't go...&quot; Around camp I looked but the sun had begun to crest the peaks. I turned to face the coming sun and a breeze over came me. Calming me. As the wind blew in my face, I faintly heard a familiar voice.<br>
&quot;Remember every morning the whispering winds come and look upon ya. Be safe Shi'yaazh....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;So all ya gathered 'round remember morn is not the time to rest. Tis da time to tighten ya grips and find a new challenge.&quot;<br>
